<p></p>

<p>By aligning dust features in depth we combine all optical logs to form an "average" dust profile, then map this composite profile to any location in the array.  Features are mapped automatically using Dynamic Time Warping (described in detail <a href="../2009JD013741.pdf">here</a>) at full ~2 mm effective resolution.  In some instances, small mapping errors may wash out fine scale features (&#60&#60;1 m) in forming the composite.</p>

<p>The optical profiles are highly repeatable and correspond closely with dust measurements in Antarctic ice cores. The composite South Pole optical profile (Fig. 2) is by far the best resolved and most stratigraphically coherent record of Antarctic dust during the last glacial period.

